The task is to prove that if Bob can force the game to end regardless of Alice's moves, then the game is guaranteed to end no matter how both players play. The game involves fixed positive integers \(a\) and \(N\), with \(N\) positive integers on a blackboard. Alice adds \(a\) to any number on her turn, and Bob divides an even number by 2 on his turn, with Alice starting and they alternating turns. The game ends when Bob has no valid moves, i.e., no even numbers are on the board.

\begin{proof}
Since Bob can force the game to end regardless of Alice's moves, it means that from the initial configuration, Bob has a strategy that ensures the game terminates in a finite number of moves for any sequence of moves Alice makes. This implies that the game graph, which consists of all possible states of the board and the moves between them, has no infinite paths starting from the initial state. If there were an infinite path, Alice could choose moves along that path to prevent the game from ending, contradicting the fact that Bob can force termination.

Therefore, all possible sequences of moves from the initial configuration must be finite, and the game is guaranteed to end no matter how Alice and Bob play.
\end{proof}
